{"title_page": "Orlando C\u00e1ceres", "text_new": "{{short description|Puerto Rican wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Orlando C\u00e1ceres\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Puerto Rican\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Orlando C\u00e1ceres''' (born 27 October 1961) is a Puerto Rican [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 57 kg|men's freestyle 57 kg]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ca/orlando-caceres-1.html |title=Orlando C\u00e1ceres Olympic Results |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caceres, Orlando}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Puerto Rican wrestler}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Orlando C\u00e1ceres\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Puerto Rican\n| sport          = [[Wrestling]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1961|10|27|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n}}\n\n'''Orlando C\u00e1ceres''' (born 27 October 1961) is a Puerto Rican [[amateur wrestling|wrestler]]. He competed in the [[Wrestling at the 1984 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's freestyle 57 kg|men's freestyle 57 kg]] at the [[1984 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ca/orlando-caceres-1.html |title=Orlando C\u00e1ceres Olympic Results |accessdate=15 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caceres, Orlando}}\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Puerto Rican male sport wrestlers]]\n[[Category:Olympic wrestlers of Puerto Rico]]\n[[Category:Wrestlers at the 1984 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in wrestling]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games bronze medalists for the United States]]\n\n\n{{PuertoRico-wrestling-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orlando_C%C3%A1ceres"}
{"title_page": "World on Fire (TV series)", "text_new": "{{short description|War drama series}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = World on Fire\n| image                    = World on Fire.jpg\n| genre                    =\n| writer                   = [[Peter Bowker]]\n| director                 = {{ubl|Chanya Button|Thomas Napper|[[Adam Smith (director)|Adam Smith]]|[[Andy Wilson (director)|Andy Wilson]]}}\n| starring                 = {{ubl|[[Julia Brown (actress)|Julia Brown]]|[[Yrsa Daley-Ward]]|[[Blake Harrison]]|[[Jonah Hauer-King]]|[[Patrick Kennedy (actor)|Patrick Kennedy]]|Ewan Mitchell|[[Parker Sawyers]]|[[Brian J. Smith]]|[[Zofia Wich\u0142acz]]|[[Tomasz Kot]]|[[Agata Kulesza]]|Victoria Mayer|[[Max Riemelt]]|Mateusz Wi\u0119c\u0142awek|Johannes Zeiler|[[Sean Bean]]|[[Lesley Manville]]|[[Helen Hunt]]|[[Arthur Darvill]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     =\n| composer                 = Dan Jones\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English <br> German <br> French <br> Polish\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 7<!-- Number of episodes aired. -->\n| executive_producer       = {{ubl|Peter Bowker|Lucy Richer|[[Damien Timmer]]|Helen Ziegler}}\n| producer                 =\n| editor                   =\n| cinematography           = S\u00f8ren Bay\n| runtime                  = 57 minutes\n| company                  = [[Mammoth Screen]]\n| distributor              = [[ITV Studios]]\n| budget                   =\n| network                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[Univisium|2:1]] [[1080p]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|9|29|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              =\n| followed_by              =\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0008zvf\n}}\n\n'''''World on Fire''''' is a [[war drama]] series written by [[Peter Bowker]]. The first series aired in 2019, and a second has been commissioned by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a29752000/world-on-fire-season-1-renewed-finale-cliffhanger/|title=World On Fire will return for season 2|last=Phillipson|first=Daisy|date=2019-11-11|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe series follows the hidden lives of ordinary people from [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[Poland]], [[France]], [[Germany]] and the USA during [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a23717436/world-on-fire-cast-plot-air-date-spoilers/ |title=BBC announces new WW2 drama World On Fire starring Helen Hunt |first=Megan |last=Sutton |date=2018-10-11 |access-date=2011-11-11 |magazine=[[Good Housekeeping]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications|Hearst UK]] |location=London |issn=01410547 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The drama switches its scenes between various locations in France, Britain, Germany and Poland. It features repeated visits to [[Paris]], [[Warsaw]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Dunkirk]].\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Sean Bean]] as Douglas Bennett, a bus conductor, pacifist and [[Shell shock|shell-shocked]] veteran of the [[Battle of the Somme]], and father to Lois and Tom.\n* [[Julia Brown (actress)|Julia Brown]] as Lois Bennett, a 21-year-old factory worker and talented singer who later joins the [[Entertainments National Service Association]].\n* [[Yrsa Daley-Ward]] as Connie Knight, a close friend, colleague and musical partner of Lois.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/yrsa| title=An interview with Yrsa Daley-Ward |website=BBC Media Centre |date=24 September 2019|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Arthur Darvill]] as Wing Commander Vernon Hunter, an RAF fighter pilot.\n* [[Blake Harrison]] as Sergeant Stan Raddings, Harry's platoon sergeant.\n* [[Jonah Hauer-King]] as Harry Chase, an interpreter at the British embassy in Warsaw who is later commissioned into the British Army, and joins the [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]].\n* [[Helen Hunt]] as Nancy Campbell, an American journalist struggling to broadcast the truth from Berlin.\n* [[Patrick Kennedy (actor)|Patrick Kennedy]] as Campbell.\n* [[Lesley Manville]] as Robina Chase, Harry's wealthy and emotionally repressed mother.\n* [[Ewan Mitchell]] as Tom Bennett, Lois's older brother, a petty criminal who later joins the Royal Navy.\n* [[Parker Sawyers]] as Albert Fallou, a Parisian jazz saxophonist and Webster's lover.\n* [[Brian J. Smith]] as Webster O'Connor, a gay American doctor based in Paris and Nancy's nephew.\n* [[Zofia Wich\u0142acz]] as Kasia Tomaszeski, a waitress from Warsaw, with whose family Harry lodges, who later joins the [[Polish resistance movement in World War II|Polish Resistance]].\n* [[Charlie Creed-Miles]] as David Walker, Harry's superior at the Warsaw embassy.\n* [[Tomasz Kot]] as Stefan Tomaszeski, a veteran of [[World War I]] and father of Kasia, Jan and Grzegorz who rejoins the Polish army.\n* [[Agata Kulesza]] as Maria Tomaszeski, Stefan's wife and mother of Kasia, Grzegorz and Jan.\n* Victoria Mayer as Claudia Rossler, a German mother living in Berlin, struggling to contain the secret of her daughter's epilepsy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/victoria |title=An interview with Victoria Mayer |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24|access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Max Riemelt]] as Schmidt, Nancy's Nazi censor and minder in Berlin.\n* Mateusz Wi\u0119c\u0142awek as Grzegorz Tomaszeski, Kasia's sickly younger brother who joins the Polish army with his father.\n* Johannes Zeiler as Uwe Rossler, Claudia's husband who runs a textile firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/johannes |title=An interview with Johannes Zeller |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24 |access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Supporting===\n* Bruno Alexander as Klaus Rossler, Claudia and Uwe's son, a German soldier.\n* Matthew Aubrey as Private Taffy Morgan, a member of Harry's platoon.\n* Eryk Biedunkiewicz as Jan Tomaszeski, Kasia's youngest brother, a schoolboy.\n* [[Jack Deam]] as Ted, manager of Lois and Connie's ENSA unit.\n* Eug\u00e9nie Derouand as Henriette Guilbert, a nurse at Webster's hospital in Paris, secretly Jewish.\n* Helene Grass as Frau Pessler, one of Uwe's employees, a committed Nazi.\n* Ansu Kabia as Eddie Knight, Connie's husband, a jazz trumpeter.\n* Jonathan McGuiness as [[Oswald Mosley|Sir Oswald Mosley]]\n* [[Ceallach Spellman]] as Private Joe Broughton, a member of Harry's platoon.\n* [[Borys Szyc]] as Konrad, a Polish army soldier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/borys |title=An interview with Borys Szyc |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24 |access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Benedict Taylor]] as Dr Drake, head of a mental hospital in Manchester.\n* Buom Tihngang as Demba, a Senegalese soldier who Harry meets in France.\n* Benjamin Wainwright as Randy, an American fighter pilot in Vernon's squadron.\n* Tomasz Zietek as Tomasz, a colleague of Kasia in the resistance.\n* Dora Zygouri as Hilda Rossler, Claudia and Uwe's daughter, who has epilepsy.\n\n==Episodes==\n===Series 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background= 800000 |overall= |series= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |viewers= |viewersR=<ref name=barb>{{Cite web |url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/four-screen-dashboard/ |title=Four-screen dashboard |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |access-date=2019-10-29 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref group=\"lower-alpha\">7-day ratings.</ref> |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |RTitle = Episode 1\n |DirectedBy = [[Adam Smith (director)|Adam Smith]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Peter Bowker]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|29|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = 1939. As the threat of the Nazi regime looms large over Europe, translator Harry Chase vows to help his Polish lover Kasia Tomaszeski flee Warsaw, but also has his sweetheart Lois Bennett, waiting for him at home in Manchester. Meanwhile, American journalist and broadcaster Nancy Campbell is at the Polish-German border, witnessing the start of the [[German invasion of Poland]]. In Paris, surgeon Webster O\u2019Connor finds the distant threat of war on his doorstep as he falls for French-African jazz musician Albert Fallou, who has been beaten up by the [[Action Fran\u00e7aise]] mob.\n |Viewers = 6.305\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |RTitle = Episode 2\n |DirectedBy = Adam Smith\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|6|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = In devastated Warsaw, Kasia makes plans to flee with grief-stricken mother Maria Tomaszeski but gets caught in a resistance cell\u2019s attack on German soldiers. Harry returns to Manchester. When he finally plucks up the courage to tell Lois the truth about Warsaw, she disarms him by declaring her love. Harry then travels to London where he\u2019s dismissed from the diplomatic services because of his conduct in Warsaw. Tom Bennett shocks father Douglas by announcing he is now a [[conscientious objector]], while in Berlin Nancy is frustrated by the growing power of the censor. In Paris, Webster and Albert are deeply in love, but their joy is overshadowed by the growing threat of prejudice they face.\n |Viewers = 5.469\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |RTitle = Episode 3\n |DirectedBy = Thomas Napper\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|13|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = After enlisting in the navy, Tom finds himself on board [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS Exeter]] in pursuit of the notorious [[German cruiser Admiral Graf Spee|Graf Spee]], a German pocket battleship which has been picking off British merchant ships for months. A huge naval battle ensues, and Tom\u2019s moral compass is reset as he watches the carnage and death around him. As Tom fights for his life, Harry and Lois face a battle of their own. Harry is now a 2nd lieutenant, and is in France with the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|BEF]], supervising the digging of foxholes and tank traps with his sergeant Stan Raddings, and trying to win the respect of his unit. When Lois arrives at the base camp to perform with [[ENSA]], Harry\u2019s two worlds collide. Lois is determined to ignore him and finds comfort in the arms of another soldier, Joe, who happens to belong to Harry\u2019s unit, and there\u2019s another shock in store for Harry when he later disciplines Joe, and finds out that Lois is pregnant.\n |Viewers = 5.374\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |RTitle = Episode 4\n |DirectedBy = [[Andy Wilson (director)|Andy Wilson]]\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|20|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = The [[Phoney War|phoney war]] is over. Harry and his unit are fighting for their lives in the town of Louvain, where German troops far outnumber those of the Allied forces. Harry is desperate to prove himself as a leader, but when the Nazis close in, Harry freezes. On the road to refuge Grzegorz Tomaszeski and Konrad are woken by a German soldier. Meanwhile, back in Warsaw, Kasia and Tomas\u2019s [[Polish resistance movement during World War II|resistance activity]] has horrific consequences as the Germans swiftly retaliate. In Paris, Webster is shocked to learn more of the rise of anti-Semitism in the city, when a Jewish couple come seeking his help. Despite hospital policy, Henriette persuades him to look after them, revealing that she too is Jewish. Secrets are also uncovered in Manchester, when Douglas guesses that Lois is hiding her pregnancy. Tom\u2019s return brings momentary relief - until he confesses that he plans to desert the Navy. Nancy submits her script to Schmidt for censor notes, and he is incredulous that she is attempting to broadcast [[Aktion T4|the euthanasia story]]. Nancy vows to broadcast the story somehow, but Schmidt threatens her: she won\u2019t if she values the Rosslers\u2019 daughter.\n |Viewers = 5.440\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |RTitle = Episode 5\n |DirectedBy = Chanya Button\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|27|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = As thousands flee Nazi-occupied Belgium, Harry, Stan and the rest of their unit take the last route out of France - the road to be [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuated]] out of [[Dunkirk]]. When the boys finally make it to a field hospital, they find an overwhelmed Webster O\u2019Connor dealing with an endless number of injured soldiers and civilians. Having stumbled across an ambulance of shell-shocked, traumatised troops (including Senegalese soldiers Demba and Ibrahim), Harry decides to stay with them. In Warsaw, Kasia\u2019s campaign of fighting and eradicating the barbarous Germans has become routine; she\u2019s worlds away from the young, carefree woman she used to be. Her part in the emerging Polish Resistance is firmly established. In Manchester, Lois and Connie are performing with ENSA at a northern airbase. They meet Wing Commander Vernon Hunter who is immediately drawn to Lois, charmed by her candour and humour. On saying goodbye, he promises to write to her. In Berlin the Rosslers are growing ever more fearful for Hilda. The only person Mr Rossler can turn to for help is Nancy.\n |Viewers = 5.995\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |RTitle = Episode 6\n |DirectedBy = Chanya Button\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|3|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = June 1940. The Nazis have [[Paris in World War II#Capture|taken Paris]] with not a bullet fired. Webster and Albert's life in the city they love will never be the same again. In Berlin, Nancy finds herself once again at the centre of the Rosslers' increasingly desperate situation as both Mr and Mrs Rossler are arrested for neglecting their patriotic duties. Back in Manchester, Harry returns home with another companion, Demba, one of the heroic Senegalese troops who stayed by Harry's side at Dunkirk. And in Warsaw, Kasia's courageous resistance continues in earnest. As she and Tomasz take ever-greater risks in fighting the Germans, the net closes in on them.\n |Viewers = 5.911\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |RTitle = Episode 7\n |DirectedBy =  Andy Wilson\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|10|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = Now part of the [[Special Operations Executive]], Harry is about to embark on his first mission. He\u2019s stunned when Major Taylor tells him he must leave for Poland on a mission to intercept a resistance group who have been identified and targeted by the Nazis. Meanwhile, in Warsaw Kasia is led to the gallows until a bomb explodes amongst the watching crowds. Lois welcomes a baby daughter into the world, and it falls to Robina to break the news to Harry that he is now a father. This spurs Harry to head to the Bennett house, where he is met by Douglas, who warns him to stay away. Lois goes to the RAF base to meet Vernon, intending to decline his proposal. His plane is the last to return, and on seeing him, she accepts instead. Harry parachutes into Poland, landing behind enemy lines. Putting his language and military skills to the test, he meets with his Polish liaison. He\u2019s led to a barn the network are using, and is at last reunited with Kasia. But the network is ambushed by the Germans and only Harry and Kasia escape, with soldiers close behind.\n |Viewers = 5.703\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe seven-part series was commissioned by the [[BBC]] in October 2017, with [[Peter Bowker]] writing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/bbc-new-drama-comedy-series-world-on-fire-the-trial-of-christine-keeler-trigonometry-north-water-1202181641/ |title=BBC Sets 'World On Fire' WWII Drama, 'The Trial Of Christine Keeler' & More |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |date=2017-10-04 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> Casting began in October 2018, with [[Helen Hunt]] and [[Lesley Manville]] amongst the first additions and filming beginning in [[Prague]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/helen-hunt-bbc-world-on-fire-1202479898/|title=Helen Hunt To Star In Peter Bowker's BBC One World War II Drama 'World On Fire' |first=Peter |last=White |date=2018-10-10 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> [[Sean Bean]] was cast in November.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/sean-bean-world-on-fire-1202509589/ |title=Sean Bean Joins Peter Bowker's BBC One WWII Epic Drama 'World On Fire' |first=Peter |last=White |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=2018-11-27 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nFilming took place in [[Chester]] in November 2018, [[Liverpool]] in March 2019 and also included other locations such as [[Prague]], [[Lytham St. Annes]], [[Wigan]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lucia |first1=Carmella de |title=Hollywood stars to film major new BBC One drama in Chester |url=https://www.cheshire-live.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/hollywood-stars-film-major-new-15450247 |access-date=2019-02-09 |newspaper=[[Chester Chronicle]] |date=2018-11-22 |df=dmy-all |publisher=[[Reach plc|Reach]] |issn=09624422}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Lorna |title=Why do these local woods look like a WW2 army camp? |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/ainsdale-woods-been-transformed-second-15803101 |access-date=2019-02-09 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |publisher=[[Reach plc|Reach]] |issn=17516277 |date=2019-02-08 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Lyme Park]].\n\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! <abbr title=Number>No.</abbr> !! Title !! Air date\n! data-sort-type=number | C7 viewers<ref name=\"barb\"/><br>(millions)\n! data-sort-type=number | C28 viewers<br>(millions)\n! data-sort-type=number | Total viewers<br>(millions)\n|- align=center\n| 1 || [[#ep1|Episode 1]] || nowrap | 29 September 2019 || 6.305 || 1.397 || 7.702\n|- align=center\n| 2 || [[#ep2|Episode 2]] || nowrap | 6 October 2019 || 5.469 || 1.272 || 6.741\n|- align=center\n| 3 || [[#ep3|Episode 3]] || nowrap | 13 October 2019 || 5.374 || 1.028 || 6.402\n|- align=center\n| 4 || [[#ep4|Episode 4]] || nowrap | 20 October 2019 || 5.440 || 0.983 || 6.423\n|- align=center\n| 5 || [[#ep5|Episode 5]] || nowrap | 27 October 2019 || 5.995 || 0.785 || 6.780\n|- align=center\n| 6 || [[#ep6|Episode 6]] || nowrap | 3 November 2019 || 5.911 || 0.578 || 6.489\n|- align=center\n| 7 || [[#ep7|Episode 7]] || nowrap | 10 November 2019 || 5.703 || 0.502|| 6.205\n|}\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n''World on Fire'' was reviewed positively by [[Lucy Mangan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]''. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/29/world-on-fire-review-ordinary-lives-caught-up-in-extraordinary-times|title=World on Fire review \u2013 ordinary lives caught up in extraordinary times|last=Mangan|first=Lucy|date=2019-09-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{IMDb title|8001092}}\n\n[[Category:2019 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mammoth Screen]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Berlin]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1940s]]\n[[Category:Works about the Dunkirk evacuation]]\n[[Category:World War II television drama series]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|War drama series}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = World on Fire\n| image                    = World on Fire.jpg\n| genre                    =\n| writer                   = [[Peter Bowker]]\n| director                 = {{ubl|Chanya Button|Thomas Napper|[[Adam Smith (director)|Adam Smith]]|[[Andy Wilson (director)|Andy Wilson]]}}\n| starring                 = {{ubl|[[Julia Brown (actress)|Julia Brown]]|[[Yrsa Daley-Ward]]|[[Blake Harrison]]|[[Jonah Hauer-King]]|[[Patrick Kennedy (actor)|Patrick Kennedy]]|Ewan Mitchell|[[Parker Sawyers]]|[[Brian J. Smith]]|[[Zofia Wich\u0142acz]]|[[Tomasz Kot]]|[[Agata Kulesza]]|Victoria Mayer|[[Max Riemelt]]|Mateusz Wi\u0119c\u0142awek|Johannes Zeiler|[[Sean Bean]]|[[Lesley Manville]]|[[Helen Hunt]]|[[Arthur Darvill]]}}\n| theme_music_composer     =\n| composer                 = Dan Jones\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = English <br> German <br> French <br> Polish\n| num_series               = 1\n| num_episodes             = 7<!-- Number of episodes aired. -->\n| executive_producer       = {{ubl|Peter Bowker|Lucy Richer|[[Damien Timmer]]|Helen Ziegler}}\n| producer                 =\n| editor                   =\n| cinematography           = S\u00f8ren Bay\n| runtime                  = 57 minutes\n| company                  = [[Mammoth Screen]]\n| distributor              = [[ITV Studios]]\n| budget                   =\n| network                  = [[BBC One]]\n| picture_format           = [[Univisium|2:1]] [[1080p]]\n| audio_format             = [[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2019|9|29|df=yes}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| preceded_by              =\n| followed_by              =\n| website                  = https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0008zvf\n}}\n\n'''''World on Fire''''' is a [[war drama]] series written by [[Peter Bowker]]. The first series aired in 2019, and a second has been commissioned by the [[BBC]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/a29752000/world-on-fire-season-1-renewed-finale-cliffhanger/|title=World On Fire will return for season 2|last=Phillipson|first=Daisy|date=2019-11-11|website=Digital Spy|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n\nThe series follows the hidden lives of ordinary people from [[United Kingdom|Britain]], [[Poland]], [[France]], [[Germany]] and the USA during [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=https://www.goodhousekeeping.com/uk/lifestyle/a23717436/world-on-fire-cast-plot-air-date-spoilers/ |title=BBC announces new WW2 drama World On Fire starring Helen Hunt |first=Megan |last=Sutton |date=2018-10-11 |access-date=2011-11-11 |magazine=[[Good Housekeeping]] |publisher=[[Hearst Communications|Hearst UK]] |location=London |issn=01410547 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> The drama switches its scenes between various locations in France, Britain, Germany and Poland. It features repeated visits to [[Paris]], [[Warsaw]], [[Manchester]], [[Berlin]] and [[Dunkirk]].\n\n==Cast==\n===Main===\n* [[Julia Brown (actress)|Julia Brown]] as Lois Bennett, a 21-year-old factory worker and talented singer who later joins the [[Entertainments National Service Association]].\n* [[Yrsa Daley-Ward]] as Connie Knight, a close friend, colleague and musical partner of Lois.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/yrsa| title=An interview with Yrsa Daley-Ward |website=BBC Media Centre |date=24 September 2019|access-date=26 September 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Arthur Darvill]] as Wing Commander Vernon Hunter, an RAF fighter pilot.\n* [[Blake Harrison]] as Sergeant Stan Raddings, Harry's platoon sergeant.\n* [[Jonah Hauer-King]] as Harry Chase, an interpreter at the British embassy in Warsaw who is later commissioned into the British Army, and joins the [[Special Operations Executive|SOE]].\n*[[Helen Hunt]] as Nancy Campbell, an American journalist struggling to broadcast the truth from Berlin.\n* [[Patrick Kennedy (actor)|Patrick Kennedy]] as Campbell.\n* [[Ewan Mitchell]] as Tom Bennett, Lois's older brother, a petty criminal who later joins the Royal Navy.\n* [[Parker Sawyers]] as Albert Fallou, a Parisian jazz saxophonist and Webster's lover.\n* [[Brian J. Smith]] as Webster O'Connor, a gay American doctor based in Paris and Nancy's nephew.\n* [[Zofia Wich\u0142acz]] as Kasia Tomaszeski, a waitress from Warsaw, with whose family Harry lodges, who later joins the [[Polish resistance movement in World War II|Polish Resistance]].\n* [[Charlie Creed-Miles]] as David Walker, Harry's superior at the Warsaw embassy.\n* [[Tomasz Kot]] as Stefan Tomaszeski, a veteran of [[World War I]] and father of Kasia, Jan and Grzegorz who rejoins the Polish army.\n* [[Agata Kulesza]] as Maria Tomaszeski, Stefan's wife and mother of Kasia, Grzegorz and Jan.\n* Victoria Mayer as Claudia Rossler, a German mother living in Berlin, struggling to contain the secret of her daughter's epilepsy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/victoria |title=An interview with Victoria Mayer |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24|access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Max Riemelt]] as Schmidt, Nancy's Nazi censor and minder in Berlin.\n* Mateusz Wi\u0119c\u0142awek as Grzegorz Tomaszeski, Kasia's sickly younger brother who joins the Polish army with his father.\n* Johannes Zeiler as Uwe Rossler, Claudia's husband who runs a textile firm.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/johannes |title=An interview with Johannes Zeller |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24 |access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Sean Bean]] as Douglas Bennett, a bus conductor, pacifist and [[Shell shock|shell-shocked]] veteran of the [[Battle of the Somme]], and father to Lois and Tom.\n* [[Lesley Manville]] as Robina Chase, Harry's wealthy and emotionally repressed mother.\n\n===Supporting===\n* Bruno Alexander as Klaus Rossler, Claudia and Uwe's son, a German soldier.\n* Matthew Aubrey as Private Taffy Morgan, a member of Harry's platoon.\n* Eryk Biedunkiewicz as Jan Tomaszeski, Kasia's youngest brother, a schoolboy.\n* [[Jack Deam]] as Ted, manager of Lois and Connie's ENSA unit.\n* Eug\u00e9nie Derouand as Henriette Guilbert, a nurse at Webster's hospital in Paris, secretly Jewish.\n* Helene Grass as Frau Pessler, one of Uwe's employees, a committed Nazi.\n* Ansu Kabia as Eddie Knight, Connie's husband, a jazz trumpeter.\n* Jonathan McGuiness as [[Oswald Mosley|Sir Oswald Mosley]]\n* [[Ceallach Spellman]] as Private Joe Broughton, a member of Harry's platoon.\n* [[Borys Szyc]] as Konrad, a Polish army soldier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/worldonfire/borys |title=An interview with Borys Szyc |website=BBC Media Centre |date=2019-09-24 |access-date=2019-09-26 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Benedict Taylor]] as Dr Drake, head of a mental hospital in Manchester.\n* Buom Tihngang as Demba, a Senegalese soldier who Harry meets in France.\n* Benjamin Wainwright as Randy, an American fighter pilot in Vernon's squadron.\n* Tomasz Zietek as Tomasz, a colleague of Kasia in the resistance.\n* Dora Zygouri as Hilda Rossler, Claudia and Uwe's daughter, who has epilepsy.\n\n==Episodes==\n===Series 1 (2019)===\n{{Episode table |background= 800000 |overall= |series= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |viewers= |viewersR=<ref name=barb>{{Cite web |url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/four-screen-dashboard/ |title=Four-screen dashboard |publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]] |access-date=2019-10-29 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref group=\"lower-alpha\">7-day ratings.</ref> |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 1\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n |RTitle = Episode 1\n |DirectedBy = [[Adam Smith (director)|Adam Smith]]\n |WrittenBy = [[Peter Bowker]]\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|9|29|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = 1939. As the threat of the Nazi regime looms large over Europe, translator Harry Chase vows to help his Polish lover Kasia Tomaszeski flee Warsaw, but also has his sweetheart Lois Bennett, waiting for him at home in Manchester. Meanwhile, American journalist and broadcaster Nancy Campbell is at the Polish-German border, witnessing the start of the [[German invasion of Poland]]. In Paris, surgeon Webster O\u2019Connor finds the distant threat of war on his doorstep as he falls for French-African jazz musician Albert Fallou, who has been beaten up by the [[Action Fran\u00e7aise]] mob.\n |Viewers = 6.305\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 2\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 2\n |RTitle = Episode 2\n |DirectedBy = Adam Smith\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|6|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = In devastated Warsaw, Kasia makes plans to flee with grief-stricken mother Maria Tomaszeski but gets caught in a resistance cell\u2019s attack on German soldiers. Harry returns to Manchester. When he finally plucks up the courage to tell Lois the truth about Warsaw, she disarms him by declaring her love. Harry then travels to London where he\u2019s dismissed from the diplomatic services because of his conduct in Warsaw. Tom Bennett shocks father Douglas by announcing he is now a [[conscientious objector]], while in Berlin Nancy is frustrated by the growing power of the censor. In Paris, Webster and Albert are deeply in love, but their joy is overshadowed by the growing threat of prejudice they face.\n |Viewers = 5.469\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 3\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 3\n |RTitle = Episode 3\n |DirectedBy = Thomas Napper\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|13|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = After enlisting in the navy, Tom finds himself on board [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS Exeter]] in pursuit of the notorious [[German cruiser Admiral Graf Spee|Graf Spee]], a German pocket battleship which has been picking off British merchant ships for months. A huge naval battle ensues, and Tom\u2019s moral compass is reset as he watches the carnage and death around him. As Tom fights for his life, Harry and Lois face a battle of their own. Harry is now a 2nd lieutenant, and is in France with the [[British Expeditionary Force (World War II)|BEF]], supervising the digging of foxholes and tank traps with his sergeant Stan Raddings, and trying to win the respect of his unit. When Lois arrives at the base camp to perform with [[ENSA]], Harry\u2019s two worlds collide. Lois is determined to ignore him and finds comfort in the arms of another soldier, Joe, who happens to belong to Harry\u2019s unit, and there\u2019s another shock in store for Harry when he later disciplines Joe, and finds out that Lois is pregnant.\n |Viewers = 5.374\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 4\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 4\n |RTitle = Episode 4\n |DirectedBy = [[Andy Wilson (director)|Andy Wilson]]\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|20|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = The [[Phoney War|phoney war]] is over. Harry and his unit are fighting for their lives in the town of Louvain, where German troops far outnumber those of the Allied forces. Harry is desperate to prove himself as a leader, but when the Nazis close in, Harry freezes. On the road to refuge Grzegorz Tomaszeski and Konrad are woken by a German soldier. Meanwhile, back in Warsaw, Kasia and Tomas\u2019s [[Polish resistance movement during World War II|resistance activity]] has horrific consequences as the Germans swiftly retaliate. In Paris, Webster is shocked to learn more of the rise of anti-Semitism in the city, when a Jewish couple come seeking his help. Despite hospital policy, Henriette persuades him to look after them, revealing that she too is Jewish. Secrets are also uncovered in Manchester, when Douglas guesses that Lois is hiding her pregnancy. Tom\u2019s return brings momentary relief - until he confesses that he plans to desert the Navy. Nancy submits her script to Schmidt for censor notes, and he is incredulous that she is attempting to broadcast [[Aktion T4|the euthanasia story]]. Nancy vows to broadcast the story somehow, but Schmidt threatens her: she won\u2019t if she values the Rosslers\u2019 daughter.\n |Viewers = 5.440\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 5\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 5\n |RTitle = Episode 5\n |DirectedBy = Chanya Button\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|10|27|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = As thousands flee Nazi-occupied Belgium, Harry, Stan and the rest of their unit take the last route out of France - the road to be [[Dunkirk evacuation|evacuated]] out of [[Dunkirk]]. When the boys finally make it to a field hospital, they find an overwhelmed Webster O\u2019Connor dealing with an endless number of injured soldiers and civilians. Having stumbled across an ambulance of shell-shocked, traumatised troops (including Senegalese soldiers Demba and Ibrahim), Harry decides to stay with them. In Warsaw, Kasia\u2019s campaign of fighting and eradicating the barbarous Germans has become routine; she\u2019s worlds away from the young, carefree woman she used to be. Her part in the emerging Polish Resistance is firmly established. In Manchester, Lois and Connie are performing with ENSA at a northern airbase. They meet Wing Commander Vernon Hunter who is immediately drawn to Lois, charmed by her candour and humour. On saying goodbye, he promises to write to her. In Berlin the Rosslers are growing ever more fearful for Hilda. The only person Mr Rossler can turn to for help is Nancy.\n |Viewers = 5.995\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 6\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 6\n |RTitle = Episode 6\n |DirectedBy = Chanya Button\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|3|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = June 1940. The Nazis have [[Paris in World War II#Capture|taken Paris]] with not a bullet fired. Webster and Albert's life in the city they love will never be the same again. In Berlin, Nancy finds herself once again at the centre of the Rosslers' increasingly desperate situation as both Mr and Mrs Rossler are arrested for neglecting their patriotic duties. Back in Manchester, Harry returns home with another companion, Demba, one of the heroic Senegalese troops who stayed by Harry's side at Dunkirk. And in Warsaw, Kasia's courageous resistance continues in earnest. As she and Tomasz take ever-greater risks in fighting the Germans, the net closes in on them.\n |Viewers = 5.911\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber = 7\n |EpisodeNumber2 = 7\n |RTitle = Episode 7\n |DirectedBy =  Andy Wilson\n |WrittenBy = Peter Bowker\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2019|11|10|df=y}}\n |ShortSummary = Now part of the [[Special Operations Executive]], Harry is about to embark on his first mission. He\u2019s stunned when Major Taylor tells him he must leave for Poland on a mission to intercept a resistance group who have been identified and targeted by the Nazis. Meanwhile, in Warsaw Kasia is led to the gallows until a bomb explodes amongst the watching crowds. Lois welcomes a baby daughter into the world, and it falls to Robina to break the news to Harry that he is now a father. This spurs Harry to head to the Bennett house, where he is met by Douglas, who warns him to stay away. Lois goes to the RAF base to meet Vernon, intending to decline his proposal. His plane is the last to return, and on seeing him, she accepts instead. Harry parachutes into Poland, landing behind enemy lines. Putting his language and military skills to the test, he meets with his Polish liaison. He\u2019s led to a barn the network are using, and is at last reunited with Kasia. But the network is ambushed by the Germans and only Harry and Kasia escape, with soldiers close behind.\n |Viewers = 5.703\n |LineColor = 800000\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\nThe seven-part series was commissioned by the [[BBC]] in October 2017, with [[Peter Bowker]] writing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2017/10/bbc-new-drama-comedy-series-world-on-fire-the-trial-of-christine-keeler-trigonometry-north-water-1202181641/ |title=BBC Sets 'World On Fire' WWII Drama, 'The Trial Of Christine Keeler' & More |first=Nancy |last=Tartaglione |date=2017-10-04 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> Casting began in October 2018, with [[Helen Hunt]] and [[Lesley Manville]] amongst the first additions and filming beginning in [[Prague]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/10/helen-hunt-bbc-world-on-fire-1202479898/|title=Helen Hunt To Star In Peter Bowker's BBC One World War II Drama 'World On Fire' |first=Peter |last=White |date=2018-10-10 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]}}</ref> [[Sean Bean]] was cast in November.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/sean-bean-world-on-fire-1202509589/ |title=Sean Bean Joins Peter Bowker's BBC One WWII Epic Drama 'World On Fire' |first=Peter |last=White |work=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|date=2018-11-27 |access-date=2019-11-03 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>\nFilming took place in [[Chester]] in November 2018, [[Liverpool]] in March 2019 and also included other locations such as [[Prague]], [[Lytham St. Annes]], [[Wigan]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lucia |first1=Carmella de |title=Hollywood stars to film major new BBC One drama in Chester |url=https://www.cheshire-live.co.uk/whats-on/film-news/hollywood-stars-film-major-new-15450247 |access-date=2019-02-09 |newspaper=[[Chester Chronicle]] |date=2018-11-22 |df=dmy-all |publisher=[[Reach plc|Reach]] |issn=09624422}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hughes |first1=Lorna |title=Why do these local woods look like a WW2 army camp? |url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/news/liverpool-news/ainsdale-woods-been-transformed-second-15803101 |access-date=2019-02-09 |newspaper=[[Liverpool Echo]] |publisher=[[Reach plc|Reach]] |issn=17516277 |date=2019-02-08 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Lyme Park]].\n\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! <abbr title=Number>No.</abbr> !! Title !! Air date\n! data-sort-type=number | C7 viewers<ref name=\"barb\"/><br>(millions)\n! data-sort-type=number | C28 viewers<br>(millions)\n! data-sort-type=number | Total viewers<br>(millions)\n|- align=center\n| 1 || [[#ep1|Episode 1]] || nowrap | 29 September 2019 || 6.305 || 1.397 || 7.702\n|- align=center\n| 2 || [[#ep2|Episode 2]] || nowrap | 6 October 2019 || 5.469 || 1.272 || 6.741\n|- align=center\n| 3 || [[#ep3|Episode 3]] || nowrap | 13 October 2019 || 5.374 || 1.028 || 6.402\n|- align=center\n| 4 || [[#ep4|Episode 4]] || nowrap | 20 October 2019 || 5.440 || 0.983 || 6.423\n|- align=center\n| 5 || [[#ep5|Episode 5]] || nowrap | 27 October 2019 || 5.995 || 0.785 || 6.780\n|- align=center\n| 6 || [[#ep6|Episode 6]] || nowrap | 3 November 2019 || 5.911 || 0.578 || 6.489\n|- align=center\n| 7 || [[#ep7|Episode 7]] || nowrap | 10 November 2019 || 5.703 || 0.502|| 6.205\n|}\n\n=== Critical reception ===\n''World on Fire'' was reviewed positively by [[Lucy Mangan]] of ''[[The Guardian]]''. <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2019/sep/29/world-on-fire-review-ordinary-lives-caught-up-in-extraordinary-times|title=World on Fire review \u2013 ordinary lives caught up in extraordinary times|last=Mangan|first=Lucy|date=2019-09-29|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BBC programme}}\n* {{IMDb title|8001092}}\n\n[[Category:2019 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2010s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British drama television series]]\n[[Category:BBC television dramas]]\n[[Category:Television series by Mammoth Screen]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Berlin]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1930s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1940s]]\n[[Category:Works about the Dunkirk evacuation]]\n[[Category:World War II television drama series]]\n", "name_user": "Necrothesp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMain", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_on_Fire_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "The Age of Surveillance Capitalism", "text_new": "{{Italic title}}\n\n'''''The Age of Surveillance Capitalism''''' is a 2018 non-fiction book by Professor [[Shoshana Zuboff]] which looks at the development of digital companies like Google and Amazon, and suggests that their business models represent a new form of capitalist accumulation that she calls \"[[surveillance capitalism]]\".<ref>{{cite news|first1=James|last1=Bridle|accessdate=2020-01-17|title=The Age of Surveillance Capitalism by Shoshana Zuboff review \u2013 we are the pawns|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/feb/02/age-of-surveillance-capitalism-shoshana-zuboff-review|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 February 2019|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=John|last1=Naughton|accessdate=2020-01-17|title='The goal is to automate us': welcome to the age of surveillance capitalism|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jan/20/shoshana-zuboff-age-of-surveillance-capitalism-google-facebook|newspaper=The Observer|date=20 January 2019|issn=0029-7712|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nZuboff states that [[Surveillance capitalism|Surveillance Capitalism]] \"unilaterally claims human experience as free raw material for translation into behavioural data [which] are declared as a proprietary ''behavioural surplus'', fed into advanced manufacturing processes known as \u2018machine intelligence\u2019, and fabricated into ''prediction products'' that anticipate what you will do now, soon, and later.\" She states that these new capitalist products \"are traded in a new kind of marketplace that I call ''behavioural futures markets''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jan/20/shoshana-zuboff-age-of-surveillance-capitalism-google-facebook|title='The goal is to automate us': welcome to the age of surveillance capitalism|last=Naughton|first=John|date=2019-01-20|work=The Observer|access-date=2020-01-16|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref>\n\nIn other words in a capitalist society, information observed from users accessing a platform such as [[facebook]]- expressing what they like and what they are less interested in. Is information that can be freely used by that platform to essentially better the experience a user will have by feeding them information that data obtained from their previous activity would have shown them to be interested in. This in many ways can be done through the use of an [[algorithm]] that automatically filters out information. The danger of surveillance capitalism is the fact that these platforms and tech companies are essentially entitled to this information by it simply being free for them to access. Leading to the backlash these companies currently face due to the fact that very few supervision by governments and users themselves in the past- has been given to how these companies have used the information gathered. With that said using the example of [[Google]] which is said to be \u201cthe pioneer of [[surveillance capitalism]]\u201d, Zuboff (2019)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Zuboff|first=Shoshana|last2=M\u00f6llers|first2=Norma|last3=Murakami Wood|first3=David|last4=Lyon|first4=David|date=2019-03-31|title=Surveillance Capitalism: An Interview with Shoshana Zuboff|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.24908/ss.v17i1/2.13238|journal=Surveillance & Society|volume=17|issue=1/2|pages=257\u2013266|doi=10.24908/ss.v17i1/2.13238|issn=1477-7487}}</ref> by introducing technological features such as \u201ccommercial models\u2026discovered by people in a time and place\u201d, Zuboff (2019)<ref name=\":0\" />. Meaning that not only are commercials being specifically filtered onto your phone but now also working hand in hand with your environment and habits such as being shown an advertisement of a local bar when walking around downtown in the evening. Advertising attempts this technical and specific can easily have an impact on the decision-making users not only in the activities they choose but in political decisions as well. Thus the idea that these companies seemingly go unchecked whilst having the power to observe and control thinking is one of the many reasons tech companies such as Google themselves are under so much scrutiny. \n\nFurthermore the freedom previously allowed to tech companies essentially comes from the idea that \u201csurveillance capitalism does not abandon established capitalist \u2018laws\u2019 such as competitive production, [[profit maximization]], productivity and growth\u201d, Zuboff (2019)<ref name=\":0\" /> as they are principles any business in a capitalistic society should aim to excel in order to be competitive. With that said Zuboff (2019)<ref name=\":0\" /> claim in article that \u201cnew logic accumulation\u2026introduces its own laws of motion\u201d. In other words being that this is a new phenomenon in capitalistic operations; it should be treated as such and be instilled with its own specific restrictions and limitations. Lastly as invasive as platforms have been in terms of accumulating information, they have also led to what is now called \u201c[[sharing economy]]\u201d, Van Dijck (2018)<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=van Dijck|first=Jos\u00e9|last2=Poell|first2=Thomas|last3=de Waal|first3=Martijn|date=2018-10-18|title=The Platform Society|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780190889760.001.0001|journal=Oxford Scholarship Online|doi=10.1093/oso/9780190889760.001.0001}}</ref> where digital information can be obtained by individuals carrying out their own surveillance capitalism through the aid of platforms themselves. Thus \u201cindividuals can greatly benefit from this transformation because it empowers them to set up business\u201d, Van Dijck (2018)<ref name=\":1\" /> these small businesses will also benefit in potentially growing faster than they would have without knowing consumer demands and wants. Leaving surveillance capitalism as a tool exceptionally well for businesses but at the same time invasive to its users.\n\n<br />\n==Reception==\n''The New Yorker'' listed ''The Age of Surveillance Capitalism'' as one of its top non-fiction books of 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/2019-in-review/our-favorite-nonfiction-books-of-2019|title=Our Favorite Nonfiction Books of 2019|last=Yorker|first=The New|date=2019-12-18|access-date=2020-01-16|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> Barack Obama also listed it as one of his favourite books of 2019, which journalism researcher Avi Asher-Schapiro noted as an interesting choice, given that the book heavily criticises the \"revolving door of personnel who migrated between Google & the Obama admin\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/article/obama-favorites-2019-the-age-of-surveillance-capitalism/|title=Obama praises book that slams his White House for its Google relationship|last=Binder|first=Matt|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\nSam DiBella, writing for the ''LSE Blog,'' criticised the book's approach which could \"inspire paralysis rather than praxis when it comes to forging collective action to counter systematic corporate surveillance.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/usappblog/2019/11/10/book-review-the-age-of-surveillance-capitalism-the-fight-for-a-human-future-at-the-new-frontier-of-power-by-shoshana-zuboff/|title=Book Review: The Age of Surveillance Capitalism: The Fight for a Human Future at the New Frontier of Power by Shoshana Zuboff|last=November 10th|last2=Reviews|first2=2019{{!}}Book|date=2019-11-10|website=USAPP|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-16|last3=Democracy|last4=Comments|first4=culture{{!}}0}}</ref>\n\n''The Financial Times'' called the book a \"masterwork of original thinking and research\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ig.ft.com/sites/business-book-award/books/2019/shortlist/the-age-of-surveillance-capitalism-by-shoshana-zuboff/|title=The Age of Surveillance Capitalism by Shoshana Zuboff|last=Graphics|first=FT Interactive|website=FT Business book of the year award|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Age of Surveillance Capitalism, The}}\n[[Category:American non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:2018 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books critical of capitalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{Italic title}}\n\n'''''The Age of Surveillance Capitalism''''' is a 2018 non-fiction book by Professor [[Shoshana Zuboff]] which looks at the development of digital companies like Google and Amazon, and suggests that their business models represent a new form of capitalist accumulation that she calls \"[[surveillance capitalism]]\".<ref>{{cite news|first1=James|last1=Bridle|accessdate=2020-01-17|title=The Age of Surveillance Capitalism by Shoshana Zuboff review \u2013 we are the pawns|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/feb/02/age-of-surveillance-capitalism-shoshana-zuboff-review|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2 February 2019|issn=0261-3077|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first1=John|last1=Naughton|accessdate=2020-01-17|title='The goal is to automate us': welcome to the age of surveillance capitalism|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/jan/20/shoshana-zuboff-age-of-surveillance-capitalism-google-facebook|newspaper=The Observer|date=20 January 2019|issn=0029-7712|via=www.theguardian.com}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nZuboff states that [[Surveillance capitalism|Surveillance Capitalism]] \"unilaterally claims human experience as free raw material for translation into behavioural data [which] are declared as a proprietary ''behavioural surplus'', fed into advanced manufacturing processes known as \u2018machine intelligence\u2019, and fabricated into ''prediction products'' that anticipate what you will do now, soon, and later.\" She states that these new capitalist products \"are traded in a new kind of marketplace that I call ''behavioural futures markets''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2019/j